Name: Rossiya Airlines
details.KeyFacts: On May 21, 2020, BIS issued against Rossiya Airlines ("Respondent") a temporary denial order for a period of 180 days in relation to the information that indicates that Rossiya is headquartered in St. Petersburg, Russia, and Aeroflot Russian Airlines JSC, a/k/a PJSC Aeroflot is Rossiya’s majority shareholder. Moreover, the Respondent was involved in exporting or reexporting 9A991 aircraft, among many others, on flights into Russia after March 2, 2022, without the required BIS authorization. Moreover, the continued operation of these aircraft by the Respondent, even on domestic routes within Russia and the company’s on-going need to acquire replacement parts and components, many of which are U.S.-origin, presents a high likelihood of imminent violations warranting imposition of a TDO. BIS further find that such apparent violations have been significant and deliberate. Therefore, issuance of the TDO is necessary in the public interest to prevent imminent violation of the Regulations and to give notice to companies and individuals in the United States and abroad that they should avoid dealing with the Respondent, in connection with export and reexport transactions involving items subject to the Regulations and in connection with any other activity subject to the Regulations.

details.KeyFacts: On May 13, 2021, BIS renewed the November 17, 2021 Denial Order, against Mahan Airways, Pejman Mahmood Kosarayanifard, Mahmoud Amini, Kerman Aviation, Sirjanco Trading, LLC, Mahan Air General Trading, LLC, Mehdi Bahrami, Al Naser Airlines, Ali Abdullah Alhay, Bahar Safwa General Trading, Sky Blue Bird Group, and Issam Shammout ("Respondents") for a period of 180 days in relation to violations of the Export Administration Regulations. Specifically, the initial TDO was issued as a result of evidence that showed that the Respondents knowingly engaged in the reexport and attempt to reexport of 9A991.b six U.S.-origin aircraft, specifically Boeing 747s, to Iran without the required licenses. Further, in February 2009, Mahan Airways participated in the export of EAR99 computer motherboards to Iran via the United Arab Emirates. In addition, as first detailed in the July 1, 2011 and August 24, 2011 orders, and discussed in subsequent renewal orders in this matter, Mahan Airways also continued to evade U.S. export control laws by operating two Airbus A310 aircraft, bearing Mahan Airways' livery and logo, on flights into and out of Iran. At the time of the July 1, 2011 and August 24, 2011 orders, these Airbus A310s were registered in France, with tail numbers F-OJHH and F-OJHI, respectively. On September 19, 2012, three Airbus A310 aircraft (tail numbers F-OJHH, F-OJHI, and EP-VIP) were designated as SDGTs. The Airbus A320 is powered with U.S.-origin engines, which are subject to the EAR and classified under Export Control Classification ("ECCN") 9A991.d. The engines are valued at more than 10 percent of the total value of the aircraft, which consequently is subject to the EAR. The aircraft is classified under ECCN 9A991.b., and its export or reexport to Iran would require U.S. Government authorization pursuant to Sections 742.8 and 746.7 of the Regulations. All 6 aircraft operated up until the day of this order. Moreover, Mahan employee attempted to initiate negotiations with a U.S. company for the purchase of an aircraft subject to the Regulations and classified under ECCN 9A610. Since December 20, 2017, BIS found evidence that Mahan airways was continuing to operate and acquire a number of aircraft and exporting or exporting aircraft parts.

Name: Nafez El Mir
details.KeyFacts:
On March 30, 2022, BIS issued a Denial Order against Nafez El Mir  ("Respondent") for a period of 10 years in relation to violations of 18 U.S.C. § 371. Specifically, the Respondent was convicted of knowingly and intentionally conspiring to willfully
export firearms, defense articles designated on the United States Munitions List, from the United States to Lebanon, without having obtained from the United States Department of State a license or written approval for the export of these defense articles. The Respondent was sentenced to 18 months imprisonment and a $200 assessment.

Name: Hicham Diab

Name: Guadalupe Horacio Garza-Cavazos
details.KeyFacts:

caliber ammunition, 20 round box of .30-30 caliber ammunition, and 12 pistol magazines. The Respondent was sentenced to 46 months in prison and a $100 assessment.

The Respondent was sentenced to 57 months imprisonment with credit for time served, three years of supervised release, and a $200 assessment.

The Respondent was sentenced to 30 months in prison, three years of supervised release, a $30,000 criminal fine, and a $100 court assessment.
